cs.SI, cs.CY, cs.SOC, cs.HC, cs.IR 

This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) because it focuses on studying social influence in online public spaces, specifically on Facebook pages. The paper also draws on a theoretical framework of social norms to explain the empirical results. 

It could also belong to cs.CY (Computers and Society) because it examines the quality of discussions in digital public squares, which has implications for how technology affects society. 

Additionally, it could fit under cs.SOC (Social and Economic Networks) because it studies social influence and norms in online social networks. 

The paper could also be categorized under cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) because it examines how different methods of ordering comments on Facebook posts affect user behavior and engagement. 

Finally, it could belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) because it measures the similarity between comments viewed and written during the study, which is a common task in information retrieval research.
